<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="387" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,1674,1915]" pageId="5" pageNumber="387">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1674,1699]" pageId="5" pageNumber="387">Remarks</emphasis>
. The new species is somewhat similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Meigen" authorityName="Meigen" box="[772,996,1674,1699]" class="Insecta" family="Chloropidae" genus="Lasiosina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="387" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cinctipes">
<emphasis box="[772,901,1675,1698]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="387">L. cinctipes</emphasis>
Meigen
</taxonomicName>
, but can be separated from the latter by the following features: legs yellow except for brown basal portion of hind femur, distal 3/5 of fore tibia, mid tibia, middle portion of hind tibia, fore and mid tarsi and hind tarsomere 5; surstylus broad, slightly parallel–sided. In 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Chloropidae" genus="Lasiosina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="387" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cinctipes">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="387">L. cinctipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, legs are yellow; surstylus is broad basally, narrowed distally and distal 1/3 incurved (Dely– 
<bibRefCitation author="Draskovits" pageId="5" pageNumber="387" refString="Dely - Draskovits, A. (1977) Neue Palaarktische Arten in der Gattung Lasiosina Becker, 1910 (Diptera, Chloropidae) Acta Zoologica Academiae Scientiarum Hungaricae, 23 (3 - 4), 267 - 278." type="journal article" year="1977">Draskovits 1977</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="387" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,1674,1915]" pageId="5" pageNumber="387">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,326,1854,1879]" pageId="5" pageNumber="387">Etymology</emphasis>
. The specific name is from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[773,892,1855,1878]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="387">recurvatus</emphasis>
(“recurved”), referring to the distally recurved postgonite.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
